msgid ""
"``numpy.trapz`` — deprecated since NumPy 2.0 (2023-08-18). Use ``numpy."
"trapezoid`` or ``scipy.integrate`` functions instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:194
msgid ""
"``disp`` function — deprecated from 2.0 release and no longer functional. "
"Use your own printing function instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:197
msgid ""
"``bias`` and ``ddof`` arguments in ``numpy.corrcoef`` — these had no effect "
"since NumPy 1.10."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:200
msgid "(`gh-29997 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29997>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:203
msgid ""
"Removed ``delimitor`` parameter from ``numpy.ma.mrecords.fromtextfile()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:204
msgid ""
"The ``delimitor`` parameter was deprecated in NumPy 1.22.0 and has been "
"removed from ``numpy.ma.mrecords.fromtextfile()``. Use ``delimiter`` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:207
msgid "(`gh-30021 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30021>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:210
msgid "``numpy.array2string`` and ``numpy.sum`` deprecations finalized"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:211
msgid ""
"The following long-deprecated APIs have been removed or converted to errors:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:213
msgid ""
"The ``style`` parameter has been removed from ``numpy.array2string``. This "
"argument had no effect since Numpy 1.14.0.  Any arguments following it, such "
"as ``formatter`` have now been made keyword-only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:217
msgid ""
"Calling ``np.sum(generator)`` directly on a generator object now raises a "
"``TypeError``.  This behavior was deprecated in NumPy 1.15.0. Use ``np."
"sum(np.fromiter(generator))`` or the python ``sum`` builtin instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:221
msgid "(`gh-30068 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30068>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:225
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:227
msgid ""
"NumPy's C extension modules have begun to use multi-phase initialisation, as "
"defined by PEP 489. As part of this, a new explicit check has been added "
"that each such module is only imported once per Python process. This comes "
"with the side-effect that deleting ``numpy`` from ``sys.modules`` and re-"
"importing it will now fail with an ``ImportError``. This has always been "
"unsafe, with unexpected side-effects, though did not previously raise an "
"error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:234
msgid "(`gh-29030 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29030>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:236
msgid ""
"``numpy.round`` now always returns a copy. Previously, it returned a view "
"for integer inputs for ``decimals >= 0`` and a copy in all other cases. This "
"change brings ``round`` in line with ``ceil``, ``floor`` and ``trunc``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:240
msgid "(`gh-29137 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29137>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:242
msgid ""
"Type-checkers will no longer accept calls to ``numpy.arange`` with ``start`` "
"as a keyword argument. This was done for compatibility with the Array API "
"standard. At runtime it is still possible to use ``numpy.arange`` with "
"``start`` as a keyword argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:247
msgid "(`gh-30147 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30147>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:249
msgid ""
"The Macro NPY_ALIGNMENT_REQUIRED has been removed The macro was defined in "
"the ``npy_cpu.h`` file, so might be regarded as semi public. As it turns "
"out, with modern compilers and hardware it is almost always the case that "
"alignment is required, so numpy no longer uses the macro.  It is unlikely "
"anyone uses it, but you might want to compile with the ``-Wundef`` flag or "
"equivalent to be sure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:256
msgid "(`gh-29094 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29094>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:260
msgid "C API changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:263
msgid "The NPY_SORTKIND enum has been enhanced with new variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:264
msgid ""
"This is of interest if you are using ``PyArray_Sort`` or "
"``PyArray_ArgSort``. We have changed the semantics of the old names in the "
"``NPY_SORTKIND`` enum and added new ones. The changes are backward "
"compatible, and no recompilation is needed. The new names of interest are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:269
msgid "``NPY_SORT_DEFAULT`` -- default sort (same value as ``NPY_QUICKSORT``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:270
msgid ""
"``NPY_SORT_STABLE``  -- the sort must be stable (same value as "
"``NPY_MERGESORT``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:271
msgid "``NPY_SORT_DESCENDING`` -- the sort must be descending"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:273
msgid ""
"The semantic change is that ``NPY_HEAPSORT`` is mapped to ``NPY_QUICKSORT`` "
"when used. Note that ``NPY_SORT_DESCENDING`` is not yet implemented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:276 ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:701
msgid "(`gh-29642 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29642>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:279
msgid "New ``NPY_DT_get_constant`` slot for DType constant retrieval"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:280
msgid ""
"A new slot ``NPY_DT_get_constant`` has been added to the DType API, allowing "
"dtype implementations to provide constant values such as machine limits and "
"special values. The slot function has the signature::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:284
msgid "int get_constant(PyArray_Descr *descr, int constant_id, void *ptr)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:286
msgid ""
"It returns 1 on success, 0 if the constant is not available, or -1 on error. "
"The function is always called with the GIL held and may write to unaligned "
"memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:289
msgid ""
"Integer constants (marked with the ``1 << 16`` bit) return ``npy_intp`` "
"values, while floating-point constants return values of the dtype's native "
"type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:292
msgid ""
"Implementing this can be used by user DTypes to provide ``numpy.finfo`` "
"values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:297
msgid ""
"A new ``PyUFunc_AddLoopsFromSpecs`` convenience function has been added to "
"the C API."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:298
msgid ""
"This function allows adding multiple ufunc loops from their specs in one "
"call using a NULL-terminated array of ``PyUFunc_LoopSlot`` structs. It "
"allows registering sorting and argsorting loops using the new ArrayMethod "
"API."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:302 ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:385
msgid "(`gh-29900 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29900>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:306
msgid "New Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:308
msgid "Let ``np.size`` accept multiple axes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:310
msgid "(`gh-29240 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29240>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:312
msgid ""
"Extend ``numpy.pad`` to accept a dictionary for the ``pad_width`` argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:314
msgid "(`gh-29273 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29273>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:317
msgid "``'same_value'`` for casting by value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:318
msgid ""
"The ``casting`` kwarg now has a ``'same_value'`` option that checks the "
"actual values can be round-trip cast without changing value. Currently it is "
"only implemented in ``ndarray.astype``. This will raise a ``ValueError`` if "
"any of the values in the array would change as a result of the cast, "
"including rounding of floats or overflowing of ints."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:324
msgid "(`gh-29129 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29129>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:327
msgid "``StringDType`` fill_value support in ``numpy.ma.MaskedArray``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:328
msgid ""
"Masked arrays now accept and preserve a Python ``str`` as their "
"``fill_value`` when using the variable‑width ``StringDType`` (kind ``'T'``), "
"including through slicing and views.  The default is ``'N/A'`` and may be "
"overridden by any valid string. This fixes issue `gh‑29421 <https://github."
"com/numpy/numpy/issues/29421>`__ and was implemented in pull request "
"`gh‑29423 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29423>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:334
msgid "(`gh-29423 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29423>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:337
msgid "``ndmax`` option for ``numpy.array``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:338
msgid ""
"The ``ndmax`` option is now available for ``numpy.array``. It explicitly "
"limits the maximum number of dimensions created from nested sequences."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:341
msgid ""
"This is particularly useful when creating arrays of list-like objects with "
"``dtype=object``. By default, NumPy recurses through all nesting levels to "
"create the highest possible dimensional array, but this behavior may not be "
"desired when the intent is to preserve nested structures as objects. The "
"``ndmax`` parameter provides explicit control over this recursion depth."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:347
msgid ""
"# Default behavior: Creates a 2D array\n"
">>> a = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4]], dtype=object)\n"
">>> a\n"
"array([[1, 2],\n"
"       [3, 4]], dtype=object)\n"
">>> a.shape\n"
"(2, 2)\n"
"\n"
"# With ndmax=1: Creates a 1D array\n"
">>> b = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4]], dtype=object, ndmax=1)\n"
">>> b\n"
"array([list([1, 2]), list([3, 4])], dtype=object)\n"
">>> b.shape\n"
"(2,)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:364
msgid "(`gh-29569 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29569>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:367
msgid "Warning emitted when using ``where`` without ``out``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:368
msgid ""
"Ufuncs called with a ``where`` mask and without an ``out`` positional or "
"kwarg will now emit a warning. This usage tends to trip up users who expect "
"some value in output locations where the mask is ``False`` (the ufunc will "
"not touch those locations). The warning can be suppressed by using "
"``out=None``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:373
msgid "(`gh-29813 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29813>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:376
msgid "DType sorting and argsorting supports the ArrayMethod API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:377
msgid ""
"User-defined dtypes can now implement custom sorting and argsorting using "
"the ``ArrayMethod`` API. This mechanism can be used in place of the "
"``PyArray_ArrFuncs`` slots which may be deprecated in the future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:381
msgid ""
"The sorting and argsorting methods are registered by passing the arraymethod "
"specs that implement the operations to the new ``PyUFunc_AddLoopsFromSpecs`` "
"function.  See the ``ArrayMethod`` API documentation for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:388
msgid "New ``__numpy_dtype__`` protocol"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:389
msgid ""
"NumPy now has a new ``__numpy_dtype__`` protocol. NumPy will check for this "
"attribute when converting to a NumPy dtype via ``np.dtype(obj)`` or any "
"``dtype=`` argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:393
msgid ""
"Downstream projects are encouraged to implement this for all dtype like "
"objects which may previously have used a ``.dtype`` attribute that returned "
"a NumPy dtype. We expect to deprecate ``.dtype`` in the future to prevent "
"interpreting array-like objects with a ``.dtype`` attribute as a dtype. If "
"you wish you can implement ``__numpy_dtype__`` to ensure an earlier warning "
"or error (``.dtype`` is ignored if this is found)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:401
msgid "(`gh-30179 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30179>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:405
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:408
msgid "Fix ``flatiter`` indexing edge cases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:410
msgid ""
"The ``flatiter`` object now shares the same index preparation logic as "
"``ndarray``, ensuring consistent behavior and fixing several issues where "
"invalid indices were previously accepted or misinterpreted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:414
msgid "Key fixes and improvements:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:416
msgid "Stricter index validation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:418
msgid ""
"Boolean non-array indices like ``arr.flat[[True, True]]`` were incorrectly "
"treated as ``arr.flat[np.array([1, 1], dtype=int)]``. They now raise an "
"index error. Note that indices that match the iterator's shape are expected "
"to not raise in the future and be handled as regular boolean indices. Use "
"``np.asarray(<index>)`` if you want to match that behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:424
msgid ""
"Float non-array indices were also cast to integer and incorrectly treated as "
"``arr.flat[np.array([1.0, 1.0], dtype=int)]``. This is now deprecated and "
"will be removed in a future version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:427
msgid ""
"0-dimensional boolean indices like ``arr.flat[True]`` are also deprecated "
"and will be removed in a future version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:430
msgid "Consistent error types:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:432
msgid ""
"Certain invalid ``flatiter`` indices that previously raised ``ValueError`` "
"now correctly raise ``IndexError``, aligning with ``ndarray`` behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:435
msgid "Improved error messages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:437
msgid ""
"The error message for unsupported index operations now provides more "
"specific details, including explicitly listing the valid index types, "
"instead of the generic ``IndexError: unsupported index operation``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:441
msgid "(`gh-28590 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/28590>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:444
msgid "Improved error handling in ``np.quantile``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:445
msgid "`np.quantile` now raises errors if:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:447
msgid "All weights are zero"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:448
msgid "At least one weight is ``np.nan``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:449
msgid "At least one weight is ``np.inf``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:451
msgid "(`gh-28595 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/28595>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:454
msgid "Improved error message for ``assert_array_compare``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:455
msgid ""
"The error message generated by ``assert_array_compare`` which is used by "
"functions like ``assert_allclose``, ``assert_array_less`` etc. now also "
"includes information about the indices at which the assertion fails."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:459
msgid "(`gh-29112 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29112>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:462
msgid "Show unit information in ``__repr__`` for ``datetime64(\"NaT\")``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:463
msgid ""
"When a ``datetime64`` object is \"Not a Time\" (NaT), its ``__repr__`` "
"method now includes the time unit of the datetime64 type. This makes it "
"consistent with the behavior of a ``timedelta64`` object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:467
msgid "(`gh-29396 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29396>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:470
msgid "Performance increase for scalar calculations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:471
msgid ""
"The speed of calculations on scalars has been improved by about a factor 6 "
"for ufuncs that take only one input (like ``np.sin(scalar)``), reducing the "
"speed difference from their ``math`` equivalents from a factor 19 to 3 (the "
"speed for arrays is left unchanged)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:476
msgid "(`gh-29819 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29819>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:479
msgid "``numpy.finfo`` Refactor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:480
msgid ""
"The ``numpy.finfo`` class has been completely refactored to obtain floating-"
"point constants directly from C compiler macros rather than deriving them at "
"runtime. This provides better accuracy, platform compatibility and corrected "
"several attribute calculations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:485
msgid ""
"Constants like ``eps``, ``min``, ``max``, ``smallest_normal``, and "
"``smallest_subnormal`` now come directly from standard C macros "
"(``FLT_EPSILON``, ``DBL_MIN``, etc.), ensuring platform-correct values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:489
msgid "The deprecated ``MachAr`` runtime discovery mechanism has been removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:491
msgid ""
"Derived attributes have been corrected to match standard definitions: "
"``machep`` and ``negep`` now use ``int(log2(eps))``; ``nexp`` accounts for "
"all exponent patterns; ``nmant`` excludes the implicit bit; and ``minexp`` "
"follows the C standard definition."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:496
msgid ""
"longdouble constants, Specifically ``smallest_normal`` now follows the C "
"standard definitions as per respecitive platform."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:499
msgid "Special handling added for PowerPC's IBM double-double format."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:501
msgid ""
"New test suite added in ``test_finfo.py`` to validate all ``finfo`` "
"properties against expected machine arithmetic values for float16, float32, "
"and float64 types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:508
msgid "Multiple axes are now supported in ``numpy.trim_zeros``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:509
msgid ""
"The ``axis`` argument of ``numpy.trim_zeros`` now accepts a sequence; for "
"example ``np.trim_zeros(x, axis=(0, 1))`` will trim the zeros from a multi-"
"dimensional array ``x`` along axes 0 and 1. This fixes issue `gh‑29945 "
"<https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/29945>`__ and was implemented in pull "
"request `gh‑29947 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29947>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:515
msgid "(`gh-29947 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29947>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:518
msgid "Runtime signature introspection support has been significantly improved"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:519
msgid ""
"Many NumPy functions, classes, and methods that previously raised "
"``ValueError`` when passed to ``inspect.signature()`` now return meaningful "
"signatures. This improves support for runtime type checking, IDE "
"autocomplete, documentation generation, and runtime introspection "
"capabilities across the NumPy API."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:525
msgid ""
"Over three hundred classes and functions have been updated in total, "
"including, but not limited to, core classes such as ``ndarray``, "
"``generic``, ``dtype``, ``ufunc``, ``broadcast``, ``nditer``, etc., most "
"methods of ``ndarray`` and scalar types, array constructor functions "
"(``array``, ``empty``, ``arange``, ``fromiter``, etc.), all ``ufuncs``, and "
"many other commonly used functions, including ``dot``, ``concat``, "
"``where``, ``bincount``, ``can_cast``, and numerous others."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:533
msgid "(`gh-30208 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30208>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:537
msgid "Performance improvements and changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:540
msgid "Performance improvements to ``np.unique`` for string dtypes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:541
msgid ""
"The hash-based algorithm for unique extraction provides an order-of-"
"magnitude speedup on large string arrays.  In an internal benchmark with "
"about 1 billion string elements, the hash-based np.unique completed in "
"roughly 33.5 seconds, compared to 498 seconds with the sort-based method – "
"about 15× faster for unsorted unique operations on strings.  This "
"improvement greatly reduces the time to find unique values in very large "
"string datasets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:548 ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:598
msgid "(`gh-28767 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/28767>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:551
msgid "Rewrite of ``np.ndindex`` using ``itertools.product``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:552
msgid ""
"The ``numpy.ndindex`` function now uses ``itertools.product`` internally, "
"providing significant improvements in performance for large iteration "
"spaces, while maintaining the original behavior and interface.  For example, "
"for an array of shape (50, 60, 90) the NumPy ``ndindex`` benchmark improves "
"performance by a factor 5.2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:558
msgid "(`gh-29165 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29165>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:561
msgid "Performance improvements to ``np.unique`` for complex dtypes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:562
msgid ""
"The hash-based algorithm for unique extraction now also supports complex "
"dtypes, offering noticeable performance gains."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:565
msgid ""
"In our benchmarks on complex128 arrays with 200,000 elements, the hash-based "
"approach was about 1.4–1.5× faster than the sort-based baseline when there "
"were 20% of unique values, and about 5× faster when there were 0.2% of "
"unique values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:570 ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:692
msgid "(`gh-29537 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29537>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:574
msgid "Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:576
msgid ""
"Multiplication between a string and integer now raises OverflowError instead "
"of MemoryError if the result of the multiplication would create a string "
"that is too large to be represented. This follows Python's behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:580
msgid "(`gh-29060 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29060>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:582
msgid ""
"The accuracy of ``np.quantile`` and ``np.percentile`` for 16- and 32-bit "
"floating point input data has been improved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:585
msgid "(`gh-29105 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29105>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:588
msgid "``unique_values`` for string dtypes may return unsorted data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:589
msgid ""
"np.unique now supports hash‐based duplicate removal for string dtypes. This "
"enhancement extends the hash-table algorithm to byte strings ('S'), Unicode "
"strings ('U'), and the experimental string dtype ('T', StringDType). As a "
"result, calling np.unique() on an array of strings will use the faster hash-"
"based method to obtain unique values. Note that this hash-based method does "
"not guarantee that the returned unique values will be sorted. This also "
"works for StringDType arrays containing None (missing values) when using "
"equal_nan=True (treating missing values as equal)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:601
msgid "Modulate dispatched x86 CPU features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:602
msgid ""
"**IMPORTANT**: The default setting for ``cpu-baseline`` on x86 has been "
"raised to ``x86-64-v2`` microarchitecture.  This can be changed to none "
"during build time to support older CPUs, though SIMD optimizations for "
"pre-2009 processors are no longer maintained."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:607
msgid ""
"NumPy has reorganized x86 CPU features into microarchitecture-based groups "
"instead of individual features, aligning with Linux distribution standards "
"and Google Highway requirements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:611
msgid "Key changes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:613
msgid ""
"Replaced individual x86 features with microarchitecture levels: ``X86_V2``, "
"``X86_V3``, and ``X86_V4``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:615
msgid "Raised the baseline to ``X86_V2``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:616
msgid ""
"Improved ``-`` operator behavior to properly exclude successor features that "
"imply the excluded feature"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:618
msgid ""
"Added meson redirections for removed feature names to maintain backward "
"compatibility"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:620
msgid ""
"Removed compiler compatibility workarounds for partial feature support (e."
"g., AVX512 without mask operations)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.4.0-notes.rst:622
msgid ""
"Removed legacy AMD features (XOP, FMA4) and discontinued Intel Xeon Phi "
"support"
msgstr ""

